But in cocos2dx display abnormal.

``` cpp
Rect TMXTilesetInfo::getRectForGID(uint32_t gid)
{
    Rect rect;
    rect.size = _tileSize;
    gid &= kTMXFlippedMask;
    gid = gid - _firstGid;

    //The reason is that _margin don't * 2
    int max_x = (int)((_imageSize.width - _margin*2 + _spacing) / (_tileSize.width + _spacing));  

    //    int max_y = (imageSize.height - margin*2 + spacing) / (tileSize.height + spacing);
    rect.origin.x = (gid % max_x) * (_tileSize.width + _spacing) + _margin;
    rect.origin.y = (gid / max_x) * (_tileSize.height + _spacing) + _margin;
    return rect;
}
```

On Mac, new project crashes as soon as I add a member to my custom cocos2d::Scene subclass.
# Steps to reproduce
1. Create a new project with `cocos new rnj -p org.myself.rnj -l cpp -d .`
2. Go `cd rnj/ && cocos run -p mac`. Everything goes as expected.
3. Create a new subclass of Scene, and add a pointer member to it. E.g.

```
class Verona: public Scene {
private:
  Sprite* mercutio;
public:
  /* Init the member with anything but nullptr. */
  Verona(): mercutio((Sprite *)0xdeadbeef) {}; // 
  CREATE_FUNC(Verona);
}
```
1. In `AppDelegate.cpp` instead of `HelloWorld::createScene()`, do `Verona::create()`.
2. `cocos run -p mac` once again and the game crashes.
# Cause

The project that generates cocos2d static lib (`cocos2d_libs.xcodeproj`) contains `CC_ENABLE_BULLET_INTEGRATION=1` preprocessor macro defined. Whereas the main generated project (`rnj.xcodeproj` in the example above) does not. Thus, the version of cocos2d::Scene in the static lib has two more actual members (namely, `_physics3DWorld` and `_physics3dDebugCamera`), that compiler doesn't expect while building the main project. A pointer member declared in a cocos2d::Scene subclass overlaps `_navMesh` pointer and in `Scene::stepPhysicsAndNavigation(...)` conditional statement

```
if (_navMesh)
{
    _navMesh->update(deltaTime);
}
```

evaluates to true and calls `update()`, which eventually leads to the crash.

I'm not sure, which of the projects contains correct settings (is the bullet integration supposed to be on or off by default), but it's certain that the settings must match.

On Android is the normal9SpriteBg placed on expected position but the corresponding native edit control is ALWAYS placed on fixed top position regardless the required/set node position.

Also, the input text is always in CAPS with no option to switch is to lower case.
Regardless what mode/flag is set.
I've tried:

n = new cc.EditBox(cc.size(size.width*0.8, 50), new cc.Scale9Sprite("editbox_bg.png"));
n.setString(this.text);
n.setFontColor(cc.color(251, 250, 250));
n.setDelegate(this);
n.setInputMode(cc.KEYBOARD_RETURNTYPE_DEFAULT);
n.setInputFlag(cc.EDITBOX_INPUT_FLAG_INITIAL_CAPS_SENTENCE);

Env: Cocos 3.5, Samsung Galaxy tablet.

Appreciate your help!
